{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17632405","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17632405"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:39:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:39:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17432"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17432","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17432"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10122"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70784"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10122","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10122"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17432"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56250"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5400"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23722"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23800"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70784","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70784"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EEpidemiologists use various measures to quantify the burden of disease in populations.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes how to calculate disease prevalence?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Number of recovered cases divided by total cases","Number of deaths divided by total population","Number of new cases divided by population at risk","Number of new cases divided by person-time at risk","Total existing cases divided by total population"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDisease prevalence is calculated as the \u003Cstrong\u003Etotal existing cases divided by total population\u003C/strong\u003E at a specific point in time. This provides a snapshot of disease burden in a population.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent other epidemiological measures:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENumber of recovered cases divided by total cases\u003C/strong\u003E represents the recovery rate, which measures the proportion of cases that resolve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENumber of deaths divided by total population\u003C/strong\u003E represents the mortality rate, which measures the frequency of deaths in a population.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENumber of new cases divided by population at risk\u003C/strong\u003E represents the incidence rate, which measures how quickly new cases develop.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENumber of new cases divided by person-time at risk\u003C/strong\u003E represents incidence density, which accounts for varying observation times in the population.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrevalence is useful for understanding the total disease burden and planning healthcare resources. It differs from incidence which measures new cases over time rather than total existing cases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Prevalence is the total number of existing cases of a condition divided by the total population at a specific point in time.","Prevalence is expressed as a proportion or percentage of the population affected.","Prevalence differs from incidence which measures new cases over a period of time."],"references":["Shultz JM, Sullivan LM, Galea S. Public Health: An Introduction to the Science and Practice of Population Health. Springer Publishing Company; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56250"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17432"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56250","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56250"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T14:01:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T14:01:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10122"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70784"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"5326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5326"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf0f","name":"Public Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-24T05:44:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-24T05:44:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"14"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"